"1280–1337":"1280–1337","1305–1364":"1305–1364","1270–1339":"1270–1339","1285–Female":"1285–Deceased","1363":"1363","1285":"1285","from 1294 to 1295":"from 1294 to 1295","1294":"1294","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","Abt 1305":"about 1305","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1336":"1336","1310":"1310","1299":"1299","1364":"1364","about 1310":"about 1310","1339":"1339","Of France":"France","Belgium":"Belgium","Camphin-en-Pévèle, Nord, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Camphin-en-Pévèle, Nord, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Gavre","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alphonse, Cecile, Chantal, Francoise, Jacques, Julien, Laurent.","French: occupational name for a blacksmith or ironworker, from a regional form of Old French <i>fevre</i> (see   Lefevre  ). Compare   Farve   and   Faver  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Faver","meanings":["Altered form of French   Favre   ‘blacksmith’ or of its cognate <b>Lefèvre</b> (see   Lefevre  ). Compare   Favor  .","English: probably in most cases an altered form of   Feaver  , partly because between the 16th and the 18th centuries its pronunciation was sometimes identical with the word favour (see 4 below).","English: occasionally perhaps also a nickname from Middle English (Old French) <i>favo(u)r</i>, Middle English <i>faver</i> ‘help, beauty, grace, benevolence’."]},{"name":"Lefevre","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Andre, Emile, Jacques, Joffre, Luc, Adrien, Antoine, Armand, Camille, Eunide, Francois, Germaine.","French and Walloon (<b>Lefèvre</b>): occupational name for a blacksmith or ironworker, Old French <i>fevre</i>, with fused masculine definite article <i>le</i>. One of the most common surnames in France from an early date, coined before the French word for smith, <i>fèvre</i> (from Latin <i>faber</i> ‘maker’), was replaced by <i>forgeron</i>. This surname was also brought to England (in the 16th century by Protestant Walloons and later reinforced by Huguenots from France). It is also established in the Flemish part of Belgium and in Haiti. See also   Lefebvre  , compare   Faver  ,   Lafaver  ,   Lafever  ,   Lefever  , and   Leffew  .","History: This surname is listed (in the form <i>Le Fèvre</i>) in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America (in the form <i>Le Fevre</i>)."]},{"name":"Favret","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Jacques, Andre, Chantel, Raoul.","French: diminutive of   Favre   ‘blacksmith’."]},{"name":"Farve","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Cecile.","Altered form of French   Favre   ‘blacksmith’."]}]},{"name":"Marguerite","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Margaret  , also used in the English-speaking world, where its use has been reinforced by the fact that the name was adopted in the 19th century for a garden flower, a large cultivated variety of daisy. <i>Margaret</i> was earlier used in English as a dialect word denoting the ox-eye daisy, and the French equivalent was borrowed into English just in time to catch the vogue for deriving girls' names from vocabulary words denoting flowers.  See also  Daisy ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Marguerite de Gavre was born from 1294 to 1295, in Belgium, her father, Erwart de Rasse de Gavre Brugelette, was 25 and her mother, Catherine De Mechelen Berthoult, was 10. She had at least 2 daughters with Baron Fastré van Ligne Heer van Ollignies."},"et":{"from 1294 to 1295–":"1294 kuni 1295–Surnud","1294–Female":"1294–Surnud","1299–1363":"1299–1363","1310–Female":"1310–Surnud","1336–Male":"1336–Surnud","1280–1337":"1280–1337","1305–1364":"1305–1364","1270–1339":"1270–1339","1285–Female":"1285–Surnud","1363":"1363","1285":"1285","from 1294 to 1295":"1294 kuni 1295","1294":"1294","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","Abt 1305":"umbes 1305","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1336":"1336","1310":"1310","1299":"1299","1364":"1364","about 1310":"umbes 1310","1339":"1339","Of France":"Prantsusmaa","Belgium":"Belgia","Camphin-en-Pévèle, Nord, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Camphin-en-Pévèle, Nord, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"from 1294 to 1295–":"vuodesta 1294 vuoteen 1295–Kuollut","1294–Female":"1294–Kuollut","1299–1363":"1299–1363","1310–Female":"1310–Kuollut","1336–Male":"1336–Kuollut","1280–1337":"1280–1337","1305–1364":"1305–1364","1270–1339":"1270–1339","1285–Female":"1285–Kuollut","1363":"1363","1285":"1285","from 1294 to 1295":"vuodesta 1294 vuoteen 1295","1294":"1294","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","Abt 1305":"noin 1305","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1336":"1336","1310":"1310","1299":"1299","1364":"1364","about 1310":"noin 1310","1339":"1339","Of France":"Ranska","Belgium":"Belgia","Camphin-en-Pévèle, Nord, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Camphin-en-Pévèle, Nord, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Ranska"},"fr":{"from 1294 to 1295–":"du 1294 au 1295–Décédée","1294–Female":"1294–Décédée","1299–1363":"1299–1363","1310–Female":"1310–Décédée","1336–Male":"1336–Décédé","1280–1337":"1280–1337","1305–1364":"1305–1364","1270–1339":"1270–1339","1285–Female":"1285–Décédée